    [postTitle] => #Concrete #Contamination #HollowBlocks

We often imagine contaminants moving deeper into a concrete element in a straight line. The truth is far more complex—especially with hollow blocks where cavities, joints, and the interfacial transition zone create tortuous, preferential paths.

In lab mock-ups with layered masonry (different mortars, varying w/c, intentional microcracks), a chloride-rich brine—denser than water—was released. Penetration looked predictable until the liquid slipped along bed and head joints, tracked the ITZ, bypassed denser zones, and collected in ungrouted cores.

These pathways—capillary pores, microcracks, cold joints, honeycombing, and voided cores—govern whether contaminants stay near the surface for years or reach reinforcing steel within months and across wall spans.

⚠️ Why HCB are tricky ⚠️

Joints & bedding quality: Partial face-shell bedding and porous/weak mortar can act like capillaries and highways for salts and CO₂.

Voids/cavities: Ungrouted or poorly grouted cores accumulate moisture and salts, enabling corrosion once rebar or ties are present.

Heterogeneity: Different density between face shells, webs, and mortar creates uneven diffusion and advection.

Detailing exposure: Splash zones, grade contact, parapets, and poorly flashed openings accelerate ingress, freeze–thaw, and efflorescence.

Inspection gap: Visual acceptance can miss sub-surface voids (grout segregation, honeycombing) that later become reservoirs.


♻️ Knowledge not shared is knowledge lost.

—
Copyrights for this belong to the respective owner. For any inquiries, claims, or removal requests, please feel free to contact me.

For more :  📌  Kossi A.
